|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Srinagar Bairiya''' is a [[town]] and [[Village Development Committee (Nepal)|Village Development Committee]]  in [[Bara District]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of south-eastern [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]] it had a population of 2,635 persons living in 431 individual households.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1|title=Nepal Census 2001|work=Nepal's Village Development Committees|publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]]|accessdate=21 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.un.org.np/maps/district-maps/central/Bara.pdf UN map of the municipalities of Bara District]\n\n{{Bara District}}\n\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Bara District]]\n\n\n{{Narayani-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pegship", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2013{{Narayani-geo-stub}}, +{{Province2NP-geo-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Srinagar_Bairiya"}
{"title_page": "Ginia Bellafante", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ginia Bellafante\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1965|03|31}}\n| birth_place  = [[United States]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| alma_mater   = \n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Journalist\n*television critic}}\n| years_active = \n}}\n\n'''Ginia Bellafante''' (born March 31, 1965) is an [[United States|American]] writer and critic for ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/b/ginia_bellafante/index.html|title=Times Topics: Ginia Bellafante|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref>  She is notorious liar too.\n\n== Career ==\nBellafante first worked as a fashion critic then spending the next five years reviewing television.<ref name=\"Ginia Bellafante\">{{cite web|url=http://unbored.net/ginia-bellafante-critic|title=Ginia Bellafante|last=X|first=Elizabeth|publisher=Unbored|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405113215/http://unbored.net/ginia-bellafante-critic|archivedate=April 5, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> She then worked at ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', as a senior reporter covering fashion, until 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,988616,00.html|title=Feminism: It's All About Me!|last=Bellafante|first=Ginia|date=June 29, 1998|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"salontime\">{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/media/1998/06/25media.html|title=Is ''Time'' brain-dead?|last=Brown|first=Janelle|date=June 25, 1998|work=Salon.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424053435/http://www.salon.com/media/1998/06/25media.html|archivedate=April 24, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she began writing for the Big City column in ''The New York Times'', \"a weekly column dedicated life, culture, politics and policy in New York City\".<ref name=\"Ginia Bellafante\" /> She has also written for the paper's culture and style sections.\n\n==Criticism==\nSome of Bellafante's writing has been criticized for its treatment of gender issues. Her 1998 ''Time'' cover story \"Is Feminism Dead?\" was critiqued by [[Erica Jong]], who said, \"''Time''{{'}}s idiotic cover story on feminism is, in short, a symptom of what's wrong, not an analysis.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Ally McBeal and Time Magazine Can't Keep the Good Women Down|first=Erica|last=Jong|authorlink=Erica Jong|url=http://observer.com/1998/07/ally-mcbeal-and-time-magazine-cant-keep-the-good-women-down|newspaper=[[The New York Observer]]|date=July 12, 1998|accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' described it as \"poorly thought-out.\"<ref name=\"salontime\"/>\n\nHer ''New York Times'' review in 2011 of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' was criticized by some as sexist for suggesting that only sexual content might motivate women to watch a complex fantasy story.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dear New York Times: A Game of Thrones Is Not Just for Boys|first=Ilana|last=Teitelbaum|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ilana-teitelbaum/game-of-thrones-hbo_b_850014.html|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|date=April 16, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Times' irks geek girls with 'Thrones' review|first=David|last=Griner|url=http://adweek.blogs.com/adfreak/2011/04/times-irks-geek-girls-with-thrones-review.html|newspaper=[[Adweek]]|date=April 15, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418195358/http://adweek.blogs.com/adfreak/2011/04/times-irks-geek-girls-with-thrones-review.html|archivedate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A Response to the NY Times Game of Thrones Review|first=Amy|last=Ratcliffe|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2011/04/a-response-to-the-ny-times-game-of-thrones-review|work=Tor.com|publisher=[[Tor Books]]|date=April 15, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Slate, New York Times to fantasy buffs: Grow up|first=Matt Zoller|last=Seitz|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/tv/feature/2011/04/16/game_of_thrones_review_of_reviewers|newspaper=Salon.com|date=April 16, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110419024238/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/tv/feature/2011/04/16/game_of_thrones_review_of_reviewers|archivedate=April 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Game of Thrones: Girls want to play, too|first=David|last=Barnett |authorlink=David Barnett (writer)|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2011/apr/18/game-of-thrones-girls-fantasy|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pull Up a Throne and Let\u2019s Talk|first=Ginia|last=Bellafante|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/19/pull-up-a-throne-and-lets-talk|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 19, 2011|accessdate=April 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/05/why-women-love-fantasy-literature/238576|title=Why Women Love Fantasy Literature|last=Rosenberg|first=Alyssa|date=May 10, 2011|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=May 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nBellafante is a native of [[Long Island]], and now lives in [[New York City]] with her husband and their son.<ref name=\"Ginia Bellafante\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/author/ginia-bellafante/ ''The New York Times Arts Beat'']\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellafante, Ginia}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:American television critics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American fashion journalists]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Women critics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n\n\n{{US-journalist-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ginia Bellafante\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1965|03|31}}\n| birth_place  = [[United States]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| alma_mater   = \n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n*Journalist\n*television critic}}\n| years_active = \n}}\n\n'''Ginia Bellafante''' (born March 31, 1965) is an [[United States|American]] writer and critic for ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/b/ginia_bellafante/index.html|title=Times Topics: Ginia Bellafante|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nBellafante first worked as a fashion critic then spending the next five years reviewing television.<ref name=\"Ginia Bellafante\">{{cite web|url=http://unbored.net/ginia-bellafante-critic|title=Ginia Bellafante|last=X|first=Elizabeth|publisher=Unbored|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405113215/http://unbored.net/ginia-bellafante-critic|archivedate=April 5, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=March 18, 2013}}</ref> She then worked at ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', as a senior reporter covering fashion, until 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,988616,00.html|title=Feminism: It's All About Me!|last=Bellafante|first=Ginia|date=June 29, 1998|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"salontime\">{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/media/1998/06/25media.html|title=Is ''Time'' brain-dead?|last=Brown|first=Janelle|date=June 25, 1998|work=Salon.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424053435/http://www.salon.com/media/1998/06/25media.html|archivedate=April 24, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, she began writing for the Big City column in ''The New York Times'', \"a weekly column dedicated life, culture, politics and policy in New York City\".<ref name=\"Ginia Bellafante\" /> She has also written for the paper's culture and style sections.\n\n==Criticism==\nSome of Bellafante's writing has been criticized for its treatment of gender issues. Her 1998 ''Time'' cover story \"Is Feminism Dead?\" was critiqued by [[Erica Jong]], who said, \"''Time''{{'}}s idiotic cover story on feminism is, in short, a symptom of what's wrong, not an analysis.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Ally McBeal and Time Magazine Can't Keep the Good Women Down|first=Erica|last=Jong|authorlink=Erica Jong|url=http://observer.com/1998/07/ally-mcbeal-and-time-magazine-cant-keep-the-good-women-down|newspaper=[[The New York Observer]]|date=July 12, 1998|accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' described it as \"poorly thought-out.\"<ref name=\"salontime\"/>\n\nHer ''New York Times'' review in 2011 of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' was criticized by some as sexist for suggesting that only sexual content might motivate women to watch a complex fantasy story.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dear New York Times: A Game of Thrones Is Not Just for Boys|first=Ilana|last=Teitelbaum|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ilana-teitelbaum/game-of-thrones-hbo_b_850014.html|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|date=April 16, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Times' irks geek girls with 'Thrones' review|first=David|last=Griner|url=http://adweek.blogs.com/adfreak/2011/04/times-irks-geek-girls-with-thrones-review.html|newspaper=[[Adweek]]|date=April 15, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110418195358/http://adweek.blogs.com/adfreak/2011/04/times-irks-geek-girls-with-thrones-review.html|archivedate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A Response to the NY Times Game of Thrones Review|first=Amy|last=Ratcliffe|url=http://www.tor.com/blogs/2011/04/a-response-to-the-ny-times-game-of-thrones-review|work=Tor.com|publisher=[[Tor Books]]|date=April 15, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Slate, New York Times to fantasy buffs: Grow up|first=Matt Zoller|last=Seitz|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/tv/feature/2011/04/16/game_of_thrones_review_of_reviewers|newspaper=Salon.com|date=April 16, 2011|accessdate=April 18, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110419024238/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/tv/feature/2011/04/16/game_of_thrones_review_of_reviewers|archivedate=April 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Game of Thrones: Girls want to play, too|first=David|last=Barnett |authorlink=David Barnett (writer)|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2011/apr/18/game-of-thrones-girls-fantasy|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pull Up a Throne and Let\u2019s Talk|first=Ginia|last=Bellafante|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/19/pull-up-a-throne-and-lets-talk|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 19, 2011|accessdate=April 25, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/05/why-women-love-fantasy-literature/238576|title=Why Women Love Fantasy Literature|last=Rosenberg|first=Alyssa|date=May 10, 2011|work=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=May 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nBellafante is a native of [[Long Island]], and now lives in [[New York City]] with her husband and their son.<ref name=\"Ginia Bellafante\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/author/ginia-bellafante/ ''The New York Times Arts Beat'']\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellafante, Ginia}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:American television critics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American fashion journalists]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Women critics]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n\n\n{{US-journalist-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "69.247.240.143", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ginia_Bellafante"}
{"title_page": "Six Flags Zhejiang", "text_new": "{{short description|Upcoming theme park in Jiaxing, China}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n|name = Six Flags Zhejiang\n|image = Six_Flags_Zhejiang_concept_art.jpg\n|caption = Artist rendering of Six Flags Zhejiang\n|location = [[Haiyan County, Zhejiang|Haiyan]], [[China]]\n|opening_date =Unknown (abandoned)\n|area = \n|season =\n|rides = \n|coasters =  \n|water_rides= \n|owner = Six Flags Amusement Parks (\u4e03\u65d7\u4e50\u56ed\uff09\n|operator= [[Maynex Private Limited]]}}\n\n'''Six Flags Zhejiang''' is an abandoned [[theme park]] in [[Jiaxing]], [[Zhejiang]], [[China]], a partnership between [[Six Flags]]. It will feature original rides and attractions, along with attractions mainly themed around ''[[Looney Tunes]]'', ''[[Garfield and Friends]]'', and ''[[Tuzki]]'', among others.<ref>{{cite news release|title=Garfield to Be Signature Character in Children's Areas of Six Flags-Branded Theme Parks in China|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170518005768/en/Garfield-Signature-Character-Children\u2019s-Areas-Flags-Branded-Theme |publisher=Business Wire|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref> In addition to a theme park, the park will be accompanied by a Six Flags Hurricane Harbor [[water park]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Frater|first=Patrick|date=2016-12-19|url=https://variety.com/2016/biz/asia/six-flags-to-build-water-park-in-china-1201945071/|title=Six Flags to Build Water Park in China|publisher=Variety|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref> Six Flags Zhejiang will be located in [[Haiyan County, Zhejiang|Haiyan]], on the coast of Hangzhou Bay. The park is approximately 45 miles from downtown Shanghai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://content.sixflags.com/haiyan/about-the-park/|title = Six Flags website |accessdate=April 1, 2017}}</ref> As of 2020, construction on the park has came to a halt, as the Riverside Investment Group has been unable to pay their debts. It\u2019s unknown wether or not construction will resume for the park.\n\n==Areas==\n===Thrillseeker Plaza===\nThe main area of the park, which will branch off to the park's other areas. The park's areas are based on other [[Six Flags]] theme parks as well as various aspects of the [[United States]].\n\n===Magic Mountain===\nThemed after [[Six Flags Magic Mountain]] in [[Valencia, Santa Clarita, California|Valencia]], [[California]].\n===Great Adventure===\nThemed after [[Six Flags Great Adventure]] in [[Jackson, New Jersey|Jackson]], [[New Jersey]].\n===Fiesta Texas===\nThemed after [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]] in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]].\n===Garfield Beach===\nA beach-themed children's area, based on the ''[[Garfield]]'' franchise by [[Jim Davis (cartoonist)|Jim Davis]].\n===Waterfront Square===\nA seaside area connected to Garfield Beach.\n===Hurricane Harbor===\nA water park, similar to other [[Six Flags Hurricane Harbor]] water parks in the US.\n==See also==\n* [[Six Flags]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://content.sixflags.com/haiyan/ Official website]\n\n{{Six Flags}}\n\n[[Category:Six Flags]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in China]]\n[[Category:Proposed amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Proposed Six Flags amusement parks]]\n\n{{China-stub}}\n{{Six-Flags-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Upcoming theme park in Jiaxing, China}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n|name = Six Flags Zhejiang\n|image = Six_Flags_Zhejiang_concept_art.jpg\n|caption = Artist rendering of Six Flags Zhejiang\n|location = [[Haiyan County, Zhejiang|Haiyan]], [[China]]\n|opening_date =June 2020 (scheduled)\n|area = \n|season =\n|rides = \n|coasters =  \n|water_rides= \n|owner = Six Flags Amusement Parks (\u4e03\u65d7\u4e50\u56ed\uff09\n|operator= [[Maynex Private Limited]]}}\n\n'''Six Flags Zhejiang''' is an upcoming [[theme park]] in [[Jiaxing]], [[Zhejiang]], [[China]], a partnership between [[Six Flags]]. It will feature original rides and attractions, along with attractions mainly themed around ''[[Looney Tunes]]'', ''[[Garfield and Friends]]'', and ''[[Tuzki]]'', among others.<ref>{{cite news release|title=Garfield to Be Signature Character in Children's Areas of Six Flags-Branded Theme Parks in China|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170518005768/en/Garfield-Signature-Character-Children\u2019s-Areas-Flags-Branded-Theme |publisher=Business Wire|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref> In addition to a theme park, the park will be accompanied by a Six Flags Hurricane Harbor [[water park]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Frater|first=Patrick|date=2016-12-19|url=https://variety.com/2016/biz/asia/six-flags-to-build-water-park-in-china-1201945071/|title=Six Flags to Build Water Park in China|publisher=Variety|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref> Six Flags Zhejiang will be located in [[Haiyan County, Zhejiang|Haiyan]], on the coast of Hangzhou Bay. The park is approximately 45 miles from downtown Shanghai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://content.sixflags.com/haiyan/about-the-park/|title = Six Flags website |accessdate=April 1, 2017}}</ref> As of 2020, construction on the park has came to a halt, as the Riverside Investment Group has been unable to pay their debts.\n\n==Areas==\n===Thrillseeker Plaza===\nThe main area of the park, which will branch off to the park's other areas. The park's areas are based on other [[Six Flags]] theme parks as well as various aspects of the [[United States]].\n\n===Magic Mountain===\nThemed after [[Six Flags Magic Mountain]] in [[Valencia, Santa Clarita, California|Valencia]], [[California]].\n===Great Adventure===\nThemed after [[Six Flags Great Adventure]] in [[Jackson, New Jersey|Jackson]], [[New Jersey]].\n===Fiesta Texas===\nThemed after [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]] in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]].\n===Garfield Beach===\nA beach-themed children's area, based on the ''[[Garfield]]'' franchise by [[Jim Davis (cartoonist)|Jim Davis]].\n===Waterfront Square===\nA seaside area connected to Garfield Beach.\n===Hurricane Harbor===\nA water park, similar to other [[Six Flags Hurricane Harbor]] water parks in the US.\n==See also==\n* [[Six Flags]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://content.sixflags.com/haiyan/ Official website]\n\n{{Six Flags}}\n\n[[Category:Six Flags]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in China]]\n[[Category:Proposed amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Proposed Six Flags amusement parks]]\n\n{{China-stub}}\n{{Six-Flags-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:4030:66c0:c9c9:432a:7616:a969", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(New information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six_Flags_Zhejiang"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nebraska", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Nebraska, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nebraska\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Nebraska]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]\n| arrival_date    = March 6, 2020\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 1,648<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx|title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) {{!}} Health & Human Services|website=dhhs.ne.gov|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://nebraska.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/4213f719a45647bc873ffb58783ffef3|title=COVID-19 Dashboard {{!}} Health & Human Services|website=dhhs.ne.gov|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us/|title=United States Coronavirus Cases {{!}} Worldometer|website=www.worldometers.info|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 33<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx Nebraska Department of Health & Human Services]\n}}\nThe 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Nebraska]] is part of an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus&nbsp;2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}). As of April 20, 2020, the [[Nebraska Department of Health & Human Services]] (DHHS) has confirmed 1,648 cases and 33 deaths in the state.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Nebraska medical cases chart}}\n\n===March===\n\nOn March 6, Governor [[Pete Ricketts]] announced that the first presumptive positive case of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) had been reported to the Nebraska DHHS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/First-Presumptive-Positive-Case-of-Coronavirus-2019-Reported-to-Nebraska-DHHS.aspx/|title=First Presumptive Positive Case Of Coronavirus 2019 Reported To Nebraska DHHS|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Nebraska DHHS set up a coronavirus (COVID-19) information line that will allow residents to get answers to general questions and receive information on resources available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Statewide-COVID-19-Information-Line-Opens-for-Residents.aspx/|title=Statewide COVID-19 Information Line Opens For Residents|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, the first and second deaths related to coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) were reported to Nebraska DHHS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Two COVID-19 Deaths Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Governor Ricketts issued an executive order to expedite the entry of medical professionals into the workforce to prepare for the possibility of a surge in COVID-19 cases and/or the unavailability of some medical professionals due to quarantine restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Issues-Executive-Order-to-Bolster-Healthcare-Workforce.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Issues Executive Order To Bolster Healthcare Workforce|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the third death related to coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) was reported in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Third-COVID-19-Death-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Third COVID-19 Death Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n\nGovernor Ricketts on April 1 urged Nebraskans to take steps to prevent the spread of COVID-19, but he fell short of issuing a [[stay-at-home order]]. 52 of 93 counties have \"directed health measures\" that include an enforceable ban on gatherings of more than 10 persons and require bars and restaurants to close their dining areas, but Ricketts does not want to extend the restrictions statewide. The state's fourth COVID-19 death was reported on March 31, a [[Buffalo County, Nebraska|Buffalo County]] man in his 90s.<ref>[https://apnews.com/4c60a12dfff86c612b1b126b5fbcbede Ricketts: Nebraskans must \u2018do better\u2019 to slow coronavirus] AP, 1 Apr 2020</ref> The fifth death in the state was reported, a Madison County resident with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Fifth-COVID-19-Death-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Fifth COVID-19 Death Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nThe state recorded its sixth death related to COVID-19, a Gage County resident, the county's first case on April 2, 2020. Colfax, Hamilton, Merrick and Otoe Counties also recently reported first cases of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Sixth-COVID-19-Death-Reported-in-State.aspx/|title=Sixth COVID-19 Death Reported In State|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, Mayor [[Jean Stothert]] admonished parkgoers to stop gathering in large groups, specifically mentioning crowding problems last weekend at Standing Bear Lake, Zorinsky Lake, Flanagan Lake, Levi Carter Park, and Walnut Grove Park. Stothert said that the City of Omaha has 260 parks but people must keep a safe 6-foot distance from others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omaha.com/news/local/mayor-stothert-stop-crowding-in-omaha-parks-or-the-city-will-close-them/article_bd2e79b2-7b14-5b28-ad09-2e6a15e539bf.html/|title=Mayor Stothert: Stop crowding in Omaha parks, or the city will close them|website=Omaha World-Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, two deaths were reported in Douglas County related to COVID-19 bringing the state total to eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-State-Bringing-Total-to-Eight.aspx/|title=Two COVID-19 Deaths Reported In State Bringing Total To Eight|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> Dr. Shane Farritor, an engineering professor at the [[University of Nebraska-Lincoln]] and a team of volunteer builders are set to build face shields ([[personal protective equipment]]) for the health care professionals at risk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ketv.com/article/unl-engineers-builders-make-face-shields-for-hospitals-battling-covid-19/32041535/|title=UNL engineers, builders make face shields for hospitals battling COVID-19|website=KETV Omaha|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, four deaths (two residents from Douglas County, one from Custer County and one from Hall County) related to COVID-19 were reported, thus bringing the state total to 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Four-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-State-Bringing-Total-to-12.aspx/|title=Four COVID-19 Deaths Reported In State Bringing Total To 12|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, Lancaster County announced its first COVID-19 related death and Madison County announced its second death adding to the state's total death toll of 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska-Bringing-Total-to-14.aspx/|title=Two COVID-19 Deaths Reported In Nebraska, Bringing Total To 14|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn April 9, Governor Ricketts proclaimed April 10\u201330, 2020 as \u201c21 Days to Stay Home and Stay Healthy in Nebraska\" and urged Nebraskans to avoid non-essential errands and limit social gatherings, as infectious disease experts project that the COVID-19 outbreak will be at or near its peak in Nebraska by the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Gov-Ricketts-Proclaims-21-Days-to-Stay-Home-and-Stay-Healthy.aspx/|title=Gov. Ricketts Proclaims \u201c21 Days To Stay Home And Stay Healthy\u201d & Unveils Six Rules To Keep Nebraska Healthy|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> State's COVID-19 related death toll reached 15 due to the six death in Douglas County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Statewide-Total-for-COVID-19-Deaths-Reaches-15.aspx/|title=Statewide Total For COVID-19 Deaths Reaches 15|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, two new deaths related to COVID-19 were reported in Hall County adding to the state's total of 17 while first cases of COVID-19 were found in Clay and Webster Counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Two-New-COVID-19-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska,-Bringing-Statewide-Total-to-17.aspx/|title=Two New COVID-19 Deaths Reported In Nebraska, Bringing Statewide Total To 17|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, first COVID-19 related death reported in Washington County and state's death toll increases to 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/18th-COVID-19-Related-Death-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=18th COVID-19 Related Death Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, state's death toll reached 20 due to COVID-19 related deaths in Douglas and Custer counties while Saline County recorded its first case of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/19th-and-20th-COVID-19-Related-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=19th And 20th COVID-19 Related Deaths Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, Morrill and Howard Counties reported their first cases while fifth death related to COVID-19 was reported in Hall County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/One-New-COVID-19-Related-Death-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=One New COVID-19 Related Death Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, two COVID-19 related deaths in Gage County and one in Douglas County increased state's death toll to 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Three-New-COVID-19-Related-Deaths-Reported-in-Nebraska.aspx/|title=Three New COVID-19 Related Deaths Reported In Nebraska|website=DHHS|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Governor Ricketts said that the social distancing guidelines will not be lifted all at once and probably some social distancing will continue until there is a vaccine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.omaha.com/news/state_and_regional/ricketts-tells-nebraskans-not-to-get-their-hopes-up-about-relaxation-of-social-distancing-rules/article_94e15c73-d6d0-5d93-98f4-15cdb84f2deb.html/|title=Ricketts tells Nebraskans not to get their hopes up about relaxation of social distancing rules|website=Omaha World-Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n\n[[File:2020 Six Rules to Keep Nebraska Healthy.pdf|thumb|Gov. Ricketts' \"Six Rules to Keep Nebraska Healthy\" during the State's response to the ongoing coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic.]]\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"|COVID-19 Cases in Nebraska<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\nUpdated April 20, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:left\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Confirmed \nCases\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |Deaths\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:right\" |County Population\n(July 2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/demo/popest/2010s-counties-detail.html#par_textimage_1383669527|title=County Population by Characteristics: 2010-2018|website=United States Census Bureau|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Adams County, Nebraska|Adams]]\n|100\n|1\n|31,511\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Antelope County, Nebraska|Antelope]]\n|1\n|0\n|6,336\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Box Butte County, Nebraska|Box Butte]]\n|1\n|0\n|10,772\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Buffalo County, Nebraska|Buffalo]]\n|55\n|1\n|49,615\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Burt County, Nebraska|Burt]]\n|1\n|0\n|6,488\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Butler County, Nebraska|Butler]]\n|1\n|0\n|8,058\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cass County, Nebraska|Cass]]\n|4\n|0\n|26,159\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cherry County, Nebraska|Cherry]]\n|1\n|0\n|5,761\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cheyenne County, Nebraska|Cheyenne]]\n|4\n|0\n|9,310\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Clay County, Nebraska|Clay]]\n|4\n|0\n|6,214\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Colfax County, Nebraska|Colfax]]\n|5\n|0\n|10,881\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Cuming County, Nebraska|Cuming]]\n|2\n|0\n|8,940\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Custer County, Nebraska|Custer]]\n|20\n|2\n|10,840\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Dakota County, Nebraska|Dakota]]\n|69\n|0\n|20,083\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Dawson\u00a0County, Nebraska|Dawson]]\n|172\n|0\n|23,709\n|-\n|[[Dixon County, Nebraska|Dixon]]\n|1\n|0\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Dodge\u00a0County, Nebraska|Dodge]]\n|18\n|0\n|36,791\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Douglas County, Nebraska|Douglas]]\n|291\n|8\n|566,880\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Franklin County, Nebraska|Franklin]]\n|3\n|0\n|3,023\n|-\n| style=\"text-a